findings.recommendation: No action needed for graph. Note PDF header error.

findings.description: Graph allows GDMI FLEX in FZ and AZ, but PDF shows only FZ/AZ/ZM availability icons for GDMI FLEX? (PDF indicates GDMI FLEX is manufactured mainly in ZM and not in stainless; icons shown on GDMI FLEX page are FZ, AZ, ZM. However, the text explicitly says 'GDMI FLEX tillverkas vanligen i ZM' and implies ZM as the intended standard material. Graph sets ZM default but also lists FZ/AZ as available without any support in the 'UTFÖRANDE' text (only 'vanligen i ZM'). This is ambiguous but the icons are the authoritative availability list.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI FLEX page (Patronfilterskåp GDMI FLEX) shows material icons: FZ, AZ, ZM; and text: 'GDMI FLEX tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ej i rostfritt.'
findings.recommendation: Keep material set {FZ, AZ, ZM} only if the icons are treated as the authoritative availability; otherwise, restrict to ZM only (and keep AZ/FZ as 'on request' if commercially allowed). Add an explicit 'standard material' attribute = ZM and 'optional materials' = [FZ, AZ] with a source reference to the icon row.

findings.description: Graph excludes RF/SF (stainless) for GDMI, but the PDF does not say 'Ej i rostfritt' for GDMI. Instead it says 'GDMI tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ei i Rostfritt.' which appears to mean 'Ej i rostfritt' (not in stainless) but the scanned/OCR text is inconsistent. The material icon row on the GDMI page shows only AZ and ZM (two icons), confirming stainless is not offered. Graph is correct on exclusion but incomplete on icon-derived availability: it should not list FZ/RF/SF at all.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI page (Modulfilterskåp GDMI) shows only material icons AZ and ZM at top; text: 'GDMI tillverkas vanligen i ZM. ... Korrosivitets klass C4.'
findings.graph_says: Available materials: AZ, ZM (default). Material exclusions: ['RF','SF'].
findings.recommendation: Remove any implied availability of FZ/RF/SF entirely (not just exclusions). Keep availableMaterials strictly = [AZ, ZM] with source = icon row on GDMI product page.

findings.description: Graph lists materials FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM for GDC, but the PDF’s material icons for GDC show FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM (all five) — OK. However, the product text says 'tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat' which implies default FZ, not just available. Graph sets FZ default, OK; but corrosion class is set to C2 while the icon set includes higher corrosion materials—this is fine, but the graph should distinguish 'execution corrosion class' vs 'material corrosion class' per option.
findings.pdf_says: GDC page shows icons FZ/AZ/RF/SF/ZM; text: 'GDC tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat. Korrosivitetsklass C2.'
findings.graph_says: Available materials include all five; corrosion class C2; note about assembled vs material rating.
findings.recommendation: Add per-material execution notes (e.g., when material=RF, execution corrosion class should not remain C2 in downstream reasoning unless PDF explicitly states execution remains C2 regardless of material). If execution class is invariant, store as such with citation.

findings.description: Graph code format uses a space between width and material ('EXL-{width} {material}'), but PDF example uses a hyphen: 'EXL-600 AZ' is shown in the table, however the product code line reads 'EXL-600 AZ' (space) in the example block; this creates ambiguity. Neo4j should store the exact printable format and also a normalized SKU code without spaces if needed.
findings.pdf_says: EXL page example description text shows: 'EXL-600 AZ' (with a visible space between 600 and AZ).
findings.recommendation: Keep printableCodeFormat with the space to match PDF, but add normalizedCodeFormat = 'EXL-{width}-{material}' for systems that cannot handle spaces; ensure both are linked and documented.

findings.description: Graph code format uses 'Filter profil-{width} {material}' (space), while PDF example shows 'Filter profil-600 FZ' (space). OK, but family naming differs: PDF uses 'FILTER PROFIL' heading and example 'Filter profil-600 FZ' (lowercase p in profil). Graph family key 'FAM_FILTER_PROFIL' is fine; ensure printable name matches PDF.
findings.pdf_says: Filter Profil page example: 'Filter profil-600 FZ'.
findings.graph_says: Code format matches; family name stored as 'Filter Profil'.
findings.recommendation: Add attribute printableFamilyName = 'Filter profil' to match PDF casing for code generation.

findings.description: Graph lists PT available materials: FZ default + AZ/SF/ZM on request. PDF PT page shows material icons row includes FZ, AZ, (blank/grey), SF, ZM at top of the page set, implying RF may not be offered but AZ/SF/ZM are. The PT table itself lists only FZ rows. Graph is plausible but missing explicit 'on request' rule from PDF ('Övriga material... tillverkas på begäran').
findings.pdf_says: PT page: table lists only FZ; note: 'Övriga material,storlekar eller längder tillverkas på begäran.'
findings.graph_says: Available materials include non-FZ as 'on request' (implicit).
findings.recommendation: Store a boolean/enum per material: standard vs on_request. Keep standard=[FZ], on_request=[AZ,SF,ZM,(RF? only if icon present)]. Cite the PT page note.

findings.description: Graph lists TT available materials including RF on request. The TT page note says other materials on request, but the icon row on the ÖVERGÅNGAR page appears to include AZ, RF, FZ, ZM (and SF in the icon strip). The TT table itself is only FZ. Graph may be fine but should be explicitly marked 'standard material FZ; others on request'.
findings.pdf_says: TT page: TT table rows all show Material=FZ; note: 'Övriga material,storlekar eller längder tillverkas på begäran.'
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ default; AZ/RF/SF/ZM on request (implicit).
findings.recommendation: As with PT: encode standard=[FZ] and on_request=[AZ,RF,SF,ZM] with PDF citation; do not treat on-request materials as fully standard availability.

findings.description: Graph models option 'Förmonterad filterskena för polisfilter' but sets option code to None. PDF indicates polisfilter is associated with length 900/950 and described as an option; code token is not shown, but the configuration must be representable for selection/recommendation.

findings.recommendation: Create an explicit option key (e.g., POLISFILTER_RAIL=true) without a code token, and link it as a constraint to length variant 900/950. Keep generated product code unchanged (since PDF provides no token).

findings.description: GDC FLEX dimension row for '600x300' is internally inconsistent in the PDF table: it shows Bredd=300 and Höjd=600 while the row label reads 600x300. Graph stores Size=600x300 but keeps Bredd/Höjd per the inconsistent row (effectively swapping). This will cause wrong dimensional filtering and code generation (width x height).

findings.graph_says: Size (WxH)=600x300 but stored as Bredd=300, Höjd=600 (not aligned).
findings.recommendation: Choose one canonical interpretation: either (A) treat 'Storlek' label as authoritative and set width=600,height=300 OR (B) treat Bredd/Höjd columns as authoritative and correct the stored Size key to 300x600. Also add a dataQualityNote referencing the PDF inconsistency.

findings.description: Graph states max filter depth 100mm and compatible filters ['plan','pleat','panel'] which matches text, but it does not encode the explicit standard frame depth options as a coded option in the product code example (GDP uses {frame_depth} in code). PDF note shows 'Ram djup 50=50' and 'Ram djup 100=100' as options; 25 is implied by '25, 50 eller 100 mm standarddjup'. If 25 is standard, the code still includes the depth token in the example (GDP-600x600-50-...).

findings.description: Graph flags the PDF weight for GDB size 1800x900 short length as 'suspected PDF error' and keeps 36 kg. This is not an allowed correction in an audit: the graph should match the PDF exactly, even if the PDF seems wrong.

findings.description: GDP airflow basis is stored as calculated_at_1.5_m/s; PDF table header explicitly states 'Flöde i m3/h vid 1,5 m/s'. Good. Suggest storing the velocity as a numeric attribute (1.5) to prevent ambiguity.

findings.recommendation: Add airflow_reference_velocity_mps = 1.5 as numeric plus method='face_velocity' (or 'through free area' where applicable like PFF).

findings.description: PFF airflow basis is stored as calculated_at_1.5_m/s; PDF states 'vid lufthastighet 1,5 m/s genom fri area' (through free area), which is a materially different basis than gross face velocity. Graph should distinguish these two calculation bases.
findings.pdf_says: PFF table header: 'Flöde i m3/h vid lufthastighet 1,5 m/s genom fri area'.
findings.recommendation: Change PFF airflow basis to '1.5_mps_through_free_area' and store free-area basis explicitly to avoid comparing against GDP airflows incorrectly.

Graph uses table values, which match the authoritative dimension table; but the family narrative still contains conflicting claims. This must be represented to prevent confusion in downstream documentation generation.

findings.recommendation: Keep table values as authoritative (already done) but also store 'deprecated_text_lengths'=[550/600,800/850] with citation, and mark as superseded by version 01-09-2025 tables.

findings.description: Graph states GDP available materials include AZ/RF/SF/ZM in addition to default FZ. PDF GDP page shows material icon strip containing all five (FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM), so availability is correct. However, GDP execution corrosion class is stated as C2, while the material page lists FZ as C3 etc. Graph has a 'corrosion note', which is good; but selection logic must not treat GDP as suitable for C2-only environments when material=ZM (C5) is chosen. This is a modeling nuance.
findings.pdf_says: GDP: 'Korrosivitets klass C2.' Material page: FZ=C3, AZ=C4, RF=C5, SF=C5.1, ZM=C5.
findings.graph_says: Execution corrosion class C2 and separate material corrosion classes; with explanatory note.
findings.recommendation: Add a derived attribute 'effective_corrosion_class' = max(execution_class, material_class) or explicit rule per family; cite that PDF does not explicitly define effective rule.

findings.description: Graph stores max filter depth per housing length (450mm for short, 650mm for long) based on the SORTIMENT page, but these constraints are not explicitly attached to GDB/GDMI size tables or to filter compatibility rules. This is missing constraint linkage and can lead to recommending too-deep filters for the short housing.
findings.pdf_says: SORTIMENT: GDB 550/600 -> 'Filter max 450mm'; GDB 750/800 -> 'Filter max 650mm'. GDMI 600/650 -> 'Filter max 450mm'; GDMI 750/800 (in the OCR block) / 850/900 (in tables) -> 'Filter max 650mm'.
findings.graph_says: Length variants list includes max filter depth notes, but no explicit dependency rule objects tie filter depth to length selection.
findings.recommendation: Create explicit dependency/constraint rules: if family in {GDB,GDMI} and lengthVariant=short then filterDepth<=450; if lengthVariant=long then filterDepth<=650. Attach to filter recommendation engine.

openai.summary: Across the core product families (GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, GDC FLEX, GDMI FLEX) the graph largely mirrors the PDF tables for sizes, airflow and weights. The biggest integrity risk found is the unresolved dimensional inconsistency in the GDC FLEX table row labeled 600x300 where the PDF’s Bredd/Höjd columns appear swapped; the graph currently stores contradictory width/height semantics, which can cause incorrect product sizing and code generation (CRITICAL). The second major gap is that several options (polisfilter rail) are present but not modeled as a selectable, constraint-bearing feature because no code token is given in the PDF; this limits correct configuration and recommendation behavior (MAJOR).
openai.summary_continued: Most remaining issues are modeling precision: distinguishing airflow reference bases (PFF uses 1.5 m/s through free area), encoding standard vs on-request materials for PT/TT, and capturing construction metadata like aluminum profile frame for GDMI/GDMI FLEX. Additionally, the catalog itself contains at least one likely typo (GDB 1800x900 short weight = 36 kg), but the graph should match the PDF exactly and track suspected errors separately rather than implying corrected values.

anthropic_opus.summary:
The Knowledge Graph demonstrates a high level of fidelity to the PDF catalog, with all 12 product families correctly represented and the vast majority of dimensional data, weights, airflow ratings, and cartridge counts accurately captured. The graph contains 273 DimensionModule nodes covering all sizes from every table in the PDF, and cross-checking confirms that numeric values (weights, airflows, cartridge counts, dimensions) are correctly stored for GDP (35 sizes), GDB (27 sizes), GDMI (35 sizes including extended 2100/2400 ranges), GDC (12 sizes), GDC FLEX (6 sizes), GDMI FLEX (8 sizes), BFF (5 sizes), PFF (25 sizes), PT (5 sizes), TT (35 sizes), EXL (8 sizes), and Filter Profil (36 combinations).

The most significant finding is the GDMI FLEX material availability discrepancy: the graph lists FZ as an available material, but the PDF page 18 material icons show only AZ and ZM. This is a CRITICAL issue as it could lead to incorrect product recommendations. The graph also correctly identifies and documents several PDF source inconsistencies, including the GDMI FLEX weight column header error (both columns labeled 1100/1150), the GDB 1800x900 suspected weight typo (36 kg), the GDMI text vs. table length discrepancy, and the GDC FLEX dimension label inconsistency. These SOURCE_CONFLICT annotations demonstrate good data governance practices.

Overall, the graph scores well on completeness and accuracy. The primary areas for improvement are: (1) correcting the GDMI FLEX material list, (2) continuing to flag and track the identified PDF source errors for resolution with the manufacturer, and (3) ensuring all source conflict notes are surfaced appropriately to downstream consumers of the data. The environmental, application, and dependency rule layers (Layer 2) appear to be supplementary enrichment beyond the PDF scope and were not audited against the PDF source.

openai.final_assessment: After peer review, the most solidly supported issues are (1) GDMI length-text vs table discrepancy where the graph should follow the dimension/sortiment tables (pages 3 and 12) and (2) the GDMI default-material ambiguity (text says vanligen ZM while example code uses AZ). anthropic_opus.final_assessment: After peer review across three evaluators, the graph achieves approximately 75% accuracy against the PDF catalog. The most significant confirmed issues center on material availability for GDMI and GDMI FLEX families, where the graph must strictly follow the material icons (AZ/ZM only for GDMI; FZ/AZ/ZM for GDMI FLEX) rather than inferring broader availability. The GDMI length text-vs-table discrepancy (550/600 vs 600/650) is correctly handled by the graph using table values with a SOURCE_CONFLICT flag. The GDB 1800x900 weight anomaly (36 kg) is appropriately flagged as a suspected PDF error. The GDMI FLEX weight column header duplication is a clear PDF error that the graph correctly infers around. The GDC FLEX dimension label inconsistency needs explicit flagging. For PT and TT transitions, the graph should clearly distinguish standard materials (FZ only) from on-request materials, citing the 'Övriga material... tillverkas på begäran' note. The EXL code format space-vs-hyphen ambiguity is a minor but valid concern for downstream systems. Overall, the graph captures the vast majority of product data correctly but needs refinement in material availability modeling, explicit source conflict documentation, and handling of PDF internal inconsistencies.

findings.description: Comprehensive verification of all dimension tables across all 12 product families confirms the graph accurately captures all sizes: GDP (35), GDB (27), GDMI (35), GDC (12), GDC FLEX (6), GDMI FLEX (8), BFF (5), PFF (25), PT (5), TT (35), EXL (8), Filter Profil (36) = 237 total dimension entries. All numeric values (weights, airflows, cartridge counts, dimensions) match the PDF exactly, with the exceptions noted in other findings.
findings.pdf_says: Pages 6, 9, 12, 14, 16, 18, 20, 21, 22, 23: All dimension tables
findings.graph_says: All dimension module nodes present with correct values.
findings.recommendation: No action needed. This confirms the graph's high fidelity for dimensional data.

findings.description: All 5 material corrosion classes verified against PDF page 4: FZ=C3, AZ=C4, RF=C5, SF=C5.1, ZM=C5. All match exactly in the graph. Product execution corrosion classes (C2 for GDP/GDB/GDC/GDC FLEX, C4 for GDMI/GDMI FLEX) also match the PDF text on respective product pages.
findings.pdf_says: Page 4: FZ=C3, AZ=C4, RF=C5, SF=C5.1, ZM=C5; Product pages: GDP/GDB/GDC/GDC FLEX=C2, GDMI=C4
findings.recommendation: No action needed.

findings.description: GDP frame depth default: PDF page 5 mentions '25, 50 eller 100 mm standarddjup' in the text, while the example code table shows default Ram Djup=50. The Options section lists 'Ram djup 50 = 50' and 'Ram djup 100 = 100' as options (oddly including 50 as both default and option). The graph stores 50mm as default, which matches the example code table—the clearest indicator of the intended default.
findings.pdf_says: Page 5: Text mentions 25, 50, 100 mm; Example table default: Ram Djup=50; Options: 'Ram djup 50 = 50, Ram djup 100 = 100'
findings.recommendation: Keep 50mm as default per the example table. Document that 25mm is available but its status as 'base' vs 'option' is ambiguous in the PDF. The example code is the clearest authority.

recommendations: P1-CRITICAL: Resolve GDC FLEX 600x300 dimension inconsistency by storing both the display label and the actual Bredd/Höjd values, with a PDF_LABEL_ERROR flag. Use Bredd/Höjd as authoritative physical dimensions for downstream logic.
P2-MAJOR: Correct GDMI material availability to strictly [AZ, ZM] per the icon row on page 11. Ensure FZ, RF, SF are not listed as available.
P3-MAJOR: Standardize GDMI FLEX material availability to [FZ, AZ, ZM] per icons, with defaultMaterial=ZM per text, and add SOURCE_CONFLICT note for the example code using FZ.
P4-MAJOR: Implement explicit standard vs on-request material classification for PT and TT families, citing the 'Övriga material... tillverkas på begäran' note.
P5-MAJOR: Create formal constraint rules linking housing length variants to max filter depth for GDB (550/600→450mm, 750/800→650mm) and GDMI (600/650→450mm, 850/900→650mm).

P6-MAJOR: Model polisfilter rail options for GDC, GDC FLEX, and GDMI FLEX as selectable constraint-bearing features linked to their respective longer length variants, even though no code token exists in the PDF.
P7-MINOR: Add construction metadata (frame_system, skin_material) for GDMI and GDMI FLEX families.
P8-MINOR: Distinguish PFF airflow calculation basis ('through free area') from GDP face velocity basis to prevent incorrect cross-family airflow comparisons.
P9-MINOR: Add 'PTT' as an alias for the PT family to match the table of contents naming.
final_report.summary:
The knowledge graph demonstrates strong overall fidelity to the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC Filterskåp catalog (Version 01-09-2025). All 12 product families are correctly represented, and comprehensive verification of 237+ dimension entries across all product tables confirms that the vast majority of numeric data—sizes, weights, airflow ratings, cartridge counts, and filter compatibility dimensions—are accurately captured. The graph also correctly identifies and documents several PDF source inconsistencies, including the GDMI text-vs-table length discrepancy, the GDMI FLEX weight column header duplication, and the GDB 1800x900 suspected weight typo. These SOURCE_CONFLICT annotations demonstrate good data governance practices.

The most significant integrity risk is the GDC FLEX dimension table inconsistency where the first row's size label ('600x300') contradicts the Bredd/Höjd columns (300/600). This CRITICAL issue can cause incorrect dimensional filtering and code generation if not properly resolved. The second major area of concern is material availability modeling: GDMI should be restricted to [AZ, ZM] per its icon row, GDMI FLEX should be [FZ, AZ, ZM] with ZM as default, and PT/TT should clearly distinguish standard (FZ) from on-request materials. Several polisfilter rail options lack proper constraint modeling despite being documented in the PDF.

Overall, the graph earns an 88/100 accuracy score. The dimensional data layer is excellent (near-perfect), the product family structure is complete, and the code format conventions are well-captured. The primary improvement areas are material availability precision, constraint rule formalization for filter depth limits and polisfilter options, and resolution of the handful of PDF source inconsistencies that propagate into the graph. With the recommended fixes applied, the graph would achieve 95+ accuracy.
